  <!-- AIO -->
  <section class="py-16 sm:py-20 bg-surface-dim bg-dots">
    <div class="max-w-4xl mx-auto px-4 sm:px-6 lg:px-8">
      <div class="section-label text-accent mb-4">Activated Roller Belt (ARB)</div>
      <h1 class="font-display text-5xl sm:text-6xl font-extrabold text-ink tracking-wide uppercase leading-tight mb-8">
        Activated Roller Belt (ARB)
      </h1>
      <div class="text-xl text-ink-muted leading-relaxed max-w-3xl">
        <p>An Activated Roller Belt (ARB) embeds small angled rollers into a modular belt surface that spin on demand to divert, singulate, align, and orient products without mechanical diverters, pusher plates, or pop-up transfer wheels. Developed and patented by <a href="https://www.intralox.com/technology/activated-roller-belt-arb" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" class="text-accent hover:text-accent-hover font-semibold">Intralox</a>, ARB technology uses friction-activated rollers beneath the belt to generate lateral forces that move products diagonally off the main conveyor path. ARB has transformed <a href="/conveyor-types/transfer-conveyors/" class="text-accent hover:text-accent-hover font-semibold">diverting and sorting</a> in parcel distribution, e-commerce fulfillment, and <a href="/industries/packaging-line-conveyors/" class="text-accent hover:text-accent-hover font-semibold">packaging lines</a> by eliminating the moving parts and maintenance demands of traditional mechanical diverters.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- How It Works -->
  <article class="py-20 bg-surface" aria-labelledby="how-heading">
    <div class="max-w-4xl mx-auto px-4 sm:px-6 lg:px-8">
      <div class="section-label text-accent mb-4">Technology</div>
      <h2 id="how-heading" class="font-display text-4xl sm:text-5xl font-extrabold text-ink tracking-wide mb-8">
        How ARB <span class="text-accent">Works</span>
      </h2>
      <div class="text-lg text-ink-muted leading-relaxed space-y-6">

        <h3 class="font-display text-2xl font-bold uppercase tracking-wider text-ink">The Roller Mechanism</h3>
        <p>Each ARB belt module contains small cylindrical rollers set at a fixed diagonal angle, either 30 degrees or 45 degrees relative to the belt travel direction. The rollers are molded into the belt module and rotate freely on their axes. When the belt runs normally (no activation), the rollers are passive. Products ride on the flat tops of the modules and travel straight ahead with the belt.</p>

        <h3 class="font-display text-2xl font-bold uppercase tracking-wider text-ink">Activation Zones</h3>
        <p>Beneath the belt, raised pads or friction strips form activation zones. When an ARB belt module passes over an activation zone, the bottom of the roller contacts the pad. Friction between the pad and roller bottom causes the roller to spin. The spinning roller exerts a lateral force on any product resting on it, pushing the product diagonally in the direction of the roller angle. Products not over an activation zone continue straight ahead.</p>

        <p>Activation zones can be placed at any point along the belt and across any portion of the belt width. A wide ARB belt can have activation zones on the left side, right side, center, or full width. This flexibility allows a single ARB conveyor to divert products to multiple destinations by placing activation zones at different positions along the belt length.</p>

        <h3 class="font-display text-2xl font-bold uppercase tracking-wider text-ink">30-Degree vs. 45-Degree Divert</h3>
        <p>The roller angle determines the divert angle. A 30-degree ARB belt diverts products at a gentler angle, producing smoother transitions and higher throughput for larger products. A 45-degree ARB belt diverts at a steeper angle, requiring less belt length to complete the divert but generating more lateral force on the product. Intralox offers both configurations. The choice depends on product characteristics, available belt length, and required throughput rate.</p>

        <h3 class="font-display text-2xl font-bold uppercase tracking-wider text-ink">No Product Gap Required</h3>
        <p>Traditional mechanical diverters (pusher plates, pop-up wheels, sliding shoe sorters) require gaps between products to operate. The diverter mechanism must retract before the next product arrives. ARB requires no gap because activation is continuous. Every product that passes over an active zone diverts regardless of spacing. This makes ARB ideal for singulation (separating products from a mass flow) and merge (combining streams) where products arrive touching each other.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </article>

  <!-- Applications -->
  <section class="py-20 bg-surface-dim bg-dots" aria-labelledby="apps-heading">
    <div class="max-w-4xl mx-auto px-4 sm:px-6 lg:px-8">
      <div class="section-label text-accent mb-4">Applications</div>
      <h2 id="apps-heading" class="font-display text-4xl sm:text-5xl font-extrabold text-ink tracking-wide mb-8">
        ARB <span class="text-accent">Applications</span>
      </h2>
      <div class="text-lg text-ink-muted leading-relaxed space-y-6">

        <h3 class="font-display text-2xl font-bold uppercase tracking-wider text-ink">Diverting & Sorting</h3>
        <p>ARB replaces mechanical diverters for routing products to multiple destinations. A single ARB belt with activation zones at different positions can divert products to 2, 3, or more takeaway lanes. Upstream scanners read barcodes and trigger activation zones based on destination. This application dominates in parcel distribution (UPS, FedEx, DHL), e-commerce fulfillment centers, and <a href="/conveyor-functions/reject-systems/" class="text-accent hover:text-accent-hover font-semibold">reject systems</a> in packaging lines.</p>

        <h3 class="font-display text-2xl font-bold uppercase tracking-wider text-ink">Singulation</h3>
        <p>Singulation separates products from a mass flow (random, overlapping, touching) into a single-file stream with gaps between products. ARB singulation uses a wide belt with diagonal activation zones that spread products apart and align them into a single lane. This replaces complex multi-stage singulation systems that use retractable walls, speed differentials, and multiple conveyor sections. Intralox's ARB singulation solutions handle up to 60-70+ packages per minute from randomly loaded induction points.</p>
        <!-- VERIFY: Singulation throughput rates against Intralox published case studies -->

        <h3 class="font-display text-2xl font-bold uppercase tracking-wider text-ink">Alignment</h3>
        <p>ARB alignment uses angled rollers to push products against a side guide, squaring them to the belt edge. Products that arrive at random orientations on a wide belt are steered against the guide and exit aligned. This feeds downstream equipment (scanners, labelers, case sealers) that requires products in a consistent position. Alignment eliminates the mechanical side-squeeze aligners and powered guide rails used in traditional systems.</p>

        <h3 class="font-display text-2xl font-bold uppercase tracking-wider text-ink">Merge</h3>
        <p>ARB merge combines two or more incoming streams into a single outbound stream. Products from side-feed conveyors enter the ARB belt, and diagonal roller activation steers them onto the main flow. Because ARB handles products without gaps, merge operations achieve higher density than mechanical merge systems. This reduces the required merge conveyor length and eliminates the pneumatic gates and photo-eye timing systems of traditional merges.</p>

        <h3 class="font-display text-2xl font-bold uppercase tracking-wider text-ink">Orientation (90-Degree Rotation)</h3>
        <p>ARB can rotate products 90 degrees by using activation zones that engage one end of the product while the belt forward motion pivots the other end. This rotates cases and cartons from long-side-leading to short-side-leading (or vice versa) without mechanical turntables. Product rotation is needed before case sealers, stretch wrappers, <a href="/conveyor-functions/collating-laning/" class="text-accent hover:text-accent-hover font-semibold">laning stations</a>, and palletizers that require a specific product orientation.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- ARB vs Traditional Diverters -->
