            </tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>
      <p class="text-sm text-ink-muted mt-4">ARB initial cost is higher but lifetime maintenance cost is significantly lower. See <a href="/resources/conveyor-cost-guide/" class="text-accent hover:text-accent-hover font-semibold">conveyor cost guide</a> for pricing factors.</p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Design Considerations -->
  <section class="py-20 bg-surface-dim bg-dots" aria-labelledby="design-heading">
    <div class="max-w-4xl mx-auto px-4 sm:px-6 lg:px-8">
      <div class="section-label text-accent mb-4">Engineering</div>
      <h2 id="design-heading" class="font-display text-4xl sm:text-5xl font-extrabold text-ink tracking-wide mb-8">
        Design <span class="text-accent">Considerations</span>
      </h2>
      <div class="text-lg text-ink-muted leading-relaxed space-y-6">

        <h3 class="font-display text-2xl font-bold uppercase tracking-wider text-ink">Belt Width & Length</h3>
        <p>ARB belt width must accommodate the widest product plus the divert path. The product must travel diagonally from its starting position to the takeaway point within the belt length. Wider belts and steeper divert angles (45 degrees) require more belt length for the product to clear the belt edge. Intralox provides layout engineering tools that calculate the required belt dimensions for specific product sizes and divert angles.</p>

        <h3 class="font-display text-2xl font-bold uppercase tracking-wider text-ink">Product Bottom Surface</h3>
        <p>ARB rollers engage the product bottom surface to generate lateral force. Products must have a relatively flat, rigid bottom. Soft-bottom products (like poly bags with loose fill) may deform around the rollers instead of being pushed. Very smooth, hard bottoms (like glass) work well. Very rough or uneven bottoms may not engage the rollers consistently. Intralox recommends product testing for unfamiliar product types.</p>

        <h3 class="font-display text-2xl font-bold uppercase tracking-wider text-ink">Activation Zone Control</h3>
        <p>Activation zones can be fixed (always active) or switchable (activated by pneumatic or electric actuators). Fixed zones suit applications where every product diverts (like a dedicated lane split). Switchable zones suit sorting applications where only selected products divert based on barcode scans or other criteria. Switchable activation adds complexity and cost but provides selective diverting capability.</p>

        <h3 class="font-display text-2xl font-bold uppercase tracking-wider text-ink">Speed & Throughput</h3>
        <p>ARB conveyor speeds typically range from 150 to 400+ FPM depending on product size and divert angle. Higher belt speeds increase throughput but reduce the time available for the roller force to complete the divert. Larger, heavier products require more time (slower belt speed or longer activation zone) to complete the divert. Intralox publishes throughput specifications for standard product categories.</p>

        <h3 class="font-display text-2xl font-bold uppercase tracking-wider text-ink">Integration with Existing Systems</h3>
        <p>ARB conveyors integrate with upstream barcode scanners, vision systems, and conveyor controls for intelligent sorting. They interface with downstream <a href="/conveyor-types/roller-conveyors/" class="text-accent hover:text-accent-hover font-semibold">roller conveyors</a>, <a href="/conveyor-types/mdr-conveyors/" class="text-accent hover:text-accent-hover font-semibold">MDR conveyors</a>, chutes, and <a href="/conveyor-types/accumulation-conveyors/" class="text-accent hover:text-accent-hover font-semibold">accumulation zones</a>. Intralox and its integration partners (system integrators like Dematic, Intelligrated, and Bastian Solutions) design complete ARB sorting systems with controls and software.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Industries -->
