            What is an activated roller belt (ARB)?
            <svg class="w-6 h-6 text-ink-muted group-open:rotate-180 transition-transform flex-shrink-0 ml-4" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" viewBox="0 0 24 24"><path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" stroke-width="2" d="M19 9l-7 7-7-7" /></svg>
          </summary>
          <div class="text-ink-muted leading-relaxed space-y-3">
            <p>A modular belt with embedded angled rollers that spin on demand to divert products diagonally. Developed by Intralox. The rollers activate when they pass over raised pads beneath the belt. No mechanical diverters, pusher plates, or pop-up wheels above the belt surface. Handles diverting, singulation, alignment, and merge.</p>
          </div>
        </details>

        <details class="group border border-border bg-surface p-6 open:pb-8">
          <summary class="font-display text-xl font-bold uppercase tracking-wider text-ink cursor-pointer list-none flex items-center justify-between group-open:mb-4">
            How does ARB technology work?
            <svg class="w-6 h-6 text-ink-muted group-open:rotate-180 transition-transform flex-shrink-0 ml-4" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" viewBox="0 0 24 24"><path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" stroke-width="2" d="M19 9l-7 7-7-7" /></svg>
          </summary>
          <div class="text-ink-muted leading-relaxed space-y-3">
            <p>Small rollers at 30 or 45 degrees are molded into belt modules. When a module passes over an activation pad beneath the belt, friction spins the roller, pushing the product diagonally. Products not over active zones travel straight. Activation zones can be fixed (always on) or switchable (selective diverting).</p>
          </div>
        </details>

        <details class="group border border-border bg-surface p-6 open:pb-8">
          <summary class="font-display text-xl font-bold uppercase tracking-wider text-ink cursor-pointer list-none flex items-center justify-between group-open:mb-4">
            ARB advantages over traditional diverters?
            <svg class="w-6 h-6 text-ink-muted group-open:rotate-180 transition-transform flex-shrink-0 ml-4" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" viewBox="0 0 24 24"><path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" stroke-width="2" d="M19 9l-7 7-7-7" /></svg>
          </summary>
          <div class="text-ink-muted leading-relaxed space-y-3">
            <p>No moving mechanical parts above the belt. No product gap requirements. Multiple divert points per belt. Gentle handling (no impact). Very low maintenance. Higher reliability. Handles mixed product sizes without adjustment. Trade-off: higher initial belt cost than simple mechanical diverters.</p>
          </div>
        </details>

        <details class="group border border-border bg-surface p-6 open:pb-8">
          <summary class="font-display text-xl font-bold uppercase tracking-wider text-ink cursor-pointer list-none flex items-center justify-between group-open:mb-4">
            What products can ARB handle?
            <svg class="w-6 h-6 text-ink-muted group-open:rotate-180 transition-transform flex-shrink-0 ml-4" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" viewBox="0 0 24 24"><path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" stroke-width="2" d="M19 9l-7 7-7-7" /></svg>
          </summary>
          <div class="text-ink-muted leading-relaxed space-y-3">
            <p>Flat-bottom products: cases, cartons, trays, totes, polybags, mailers, parcels. Sizes from 6 inches to 36+ inches. Handles wide product variety without changeover. Products must have a flat, relatively rigid bottom for roller engagement. Very heavy products (over 100 lbs) or soft-bottom items may not divert reliably.</p>
          </div>
        </details>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Related -->
  <section class="py-16 bg-ink-light" aria-labelledby="related-heading">
